# Kubernetes Command-Line Reference Guide

## Basic kubectl Commands

### Cluster Information
```bash
kubectl cluster-info                          # Display cluster information
kubectl version                               # Show client and server versions
kubectl api-versions                          # List API versions
kubectl api-resources                         # List all API resources
kubectl config view                           # Display kubeconfig settings
kubectl config get-contexts                   # List all contexts
kubectl config current-context                # Show current context
kubectl config use-context <context-name>    # Switch to a context
```

### Node Management
```bash
kubectl get nodes                             # List all nodes
kubectl describe node <node-name>             # Get detailed node info
kubectl top nodes                             # Show node resource usage
kubectl cordon <node-name>                    # Mark node as unschedulable
kubectl uncordon <node-name>                  # Mark node as schedulable
kubectl drain <node-name>                     # Drain node for maintenance
kubectl taint nodes <node-name> key=value:NoSchedule  # Add taint to node
```

### Namespace Management
```bash
kubectl get namespaces                        # List all namespaces
kubectl create namespace <namespace-name>    # Create a namespace
kubectl delete namespace <namespace-name>    # Delete a namespace
kubectl describe namespace <namespace-name>  # Get namespace details
kubectl config set-context --current --namespace=<ns>  # Set default namespace
```

## Pod Management

### Viewing Pods
```bash
kubectl get pods                              # List pods in default namespace
kubectl get pods -A                           # List pods in all namespaces
kubectl get pods -n <namespace>               # List pods in specific namespace
kubectl get pods -o wide                      # Show more pod details
kubectl get pods -o yaml                      # Output in YAML format
kubectl get pods -o json                      # Output in JSON format
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>               # Get detailed pod info
kubectl get pods --sort-by='.status.phase'   # Sort pods by phase
kubectl get pods --selector=app=myapp        # Filter pods by labels
```

### Pod Operations
```bash
kubectl create -f <file.yaml>                 # Create pod from YAML
kubectl apply -f <file.yaml>                  # Apply YAML (create/update)
kubectl delete pod <pod-name>                 # Delete a pod
kubectl delete pod <pod-name> --grace-period=0 --force  # Force delete pod
kubectl logs <pod-name>                       # View pod logs
kubectl logs <pod-name> -c <container>        # View specific container logs
kubectl logs <pod-name> -f                    # Stream pod logs
kubectl logs <pod-name> --previous            # View logs from crashed container
kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- /bin/bash     # Execute command in pod
kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -c <container> -- /bin/sh  # Exec in specific container
kubectl port-forward <pod-name> 8080:8080    # Forward local port to pod
kubectl attach <pod-name> -i -t               # Attach to running pod
kubectl cp <pod-name>:/path/file ./file      # Copy file from pod
kubectl cp ./file <pod-name>:/path/file      # Copy file to pod
```

### Pod Scaling & Management
```bash
kubectl scale deployment <deployment> --replicas=3  # Scale deployment
kubectl set image deployment/<dep> image=v2  # Update deployment image
kubectl rollout status deployment/<name>     # Check rollout status
kubectl rollout history deployment/<name>    # View rollout history
kubectl rollout undo deployment/<name>       # Rollback to previous version
kubectl rollout undo deployment/<name> --to-revision=2  # Rollback to specific version
```

## Deployment Management

### Viewing Deployments
```bash
kubectl get deployments                       # List all deployments
kubectl get deployments -A                    # List deployments in all namespaces
kubectl describe deployment <deployment>     # Get deployment details
kubectl get deployment <deployment> -o yaml  # Export deployment YAML
```

### Deployment Operations
```bash
kubectl create deployment <name> --image=<image>  # Create deployment
kubectl apply -f <deployment.yaml>           # Apply deployment YAML
kubectl delete deployment <deployment>       # Delete deployment
kubectl edit deployment <deployment>         # Edit deployment in editor
kubectl set image deployment/<dep> container=<image>  # Update image
kubectl set resources deployment/<dep> --limits=cpu=500m,memory=512Mi  # Set resources
kubectl autoscale deployment <dep> --min=1 --max=5 --cpu-percent=80  # Enable autoscaling
kubectl delete deployment <dep> --cascade=orphan  # Delete without deleting pods
```

## Service Management

### Viewing Services
```bash
kubectl get services                          # List all services
kubectl get svc                               # Short form
kubectl get svc -A                            # All services across namespaces
kubectl describe service <service-name>      # Get service details
kubectl get endpoints <service-name>         # View service endpoints
```

### Service Operations
```bash
kubectl expose pod <pod-name> --port=8080   # Create service from pod
kubectl expose deployment <dep> --type=LoadBalancer --port=80 --target-port=8080
kubectl create service clusterip <name> --tcp=5678:8080
kubectl delete service <service-name>        # Delete service
kubectl edit service <service-name>          # Edit service
kubectl port-forward svc/<service> 8080:8080  # Port forward to service
```

