kubectl diff -k <directory>                  # Show differences
kubectl delete -k <directory>                # Delete from Kustomization
```

## Useful Flags & Options

### Common Flags
```bash
-n, --namespace=<namespace>                  # Specify namespace
-A, --all-namespaces                         # All namespaces
-o, --output=<format>                        # Output format (yaml, json, wide, custom-columns)
-l, --selector=<label-selector>              # Filter by labels
--field-selector=<field-selector>            # Filter by fields
-w, --watch                                  # Watch for changes
--sort-by=<field>                            # Sort results
--dry-run=<mode>                             # Dry run (client or server)
-f, --filename=<file>                        # File path
-R, --recursive                              # Recursive
--context=<context>                          # Specify context
-v, --v=<level>                              # Verbosity level
--all                                        # All resources
--cascade=<mode>                             # Delete cascade (background, foreground, orphan)
```

## Complete Examples

### Example 1: Create and Expose Deployment
```bash
kubectl create deployment nginx --image=nginx:latest
kubectl expose deployment nginx --type=LoadBalancer --port=80 --target-port=8080
kubectl get svc nginx
```

### Example 2: Scale and Update
```bash
kubectl scale deployment nginx --replicas=5
kubectl set image deployment/nginx nginx=nginx:1.19 --record
kubectl rollout status deployment/nginx
```

### Example 3: Check Resource Usage
```bash
kubectl top nodes
kubectl top pods -A
kubectl describe node <node-name>
```

### Example 4: Debug Pod
```bash
kubectl describe pod <pod-name>
kubectl logs <pod-name>
kubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- /bin/bash
```

### Example 5: Create ConfigMap & Use in Pod
```bash
kubectl create configmap app-config --from-literal=app.env=production
kubectl set env deployment/myapp --from=configmap/app-config
```

## Advanced Tips

- Use `kubectl explain <resource>` to get API documentation
- Use `--dry-run=client` to preview changes before applying
- Use `--watch` flag to monitor resources in real-time
- Use `-o custom-columns` for custom output formatting
- Use `kubectl api-resources` to see all available resources
- Use context switching for multi-cluster management
- Use labels and selectors for flexible resource queries
- Use namespaces to organize and isolate workloads
